Fli%3E%5Cn%3Cli%3EIt's%20the%20final%20chromosome%20in%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Ftelomere-consortium-scientists-map-full-human-genome-for-first-time-2022-4%5C%22%3Ehuman%20genome%3C%2Fa%3E%20that%20researchers%20hadn't%20fully%20sequenced.%C2%A0%3C%2Fli%3E%5Cn%3Cli%3EThe%20new%20reference%20could%20help%20researchers%20better%20understand%20infertility%20and%20some%20types%20of%20cancer.%3C%2Fli%3E%5Cn%3C%2Ful%3E%3Cp%3EDecades%20ago%2C%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov%2Fpmc%2Farticles%2FPMC79676%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Eresearchers%20referred%3C%2Fa%3E%20to%20the%20human%20Y%20chromosome%20as%20a%20%26quot%3Bfunctional%20wasteland%2C%26quot%3B%20among%20other%20names.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EA%20huge%20amount%20of%20its%20genome%20was%20unsequenced%2C%20and%20it%20was%20difficult%20to%20know%20how%20some%20of%20its%20protein-coding%20genes%20worked.%20But%20not%20anymore.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ETwo%20new%20papers%2C%20both%20published%20today%20in%20Nature%2C%20shed%20light%20on%20some%20of%20the%20Y%20chromosome's%20mysteries.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EEach%20paper's%20results%20could%20offer%20new%20insight%20for%20research%20into%20reproduction%2C%20some%20types%20of%20cancer%2C%20aging%2C%20and%20human%20evolution.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E%3Cstrong%3EFinally%20mapping%20the%20Y%20chromosome%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1038%2Fs41586-023-06457-y%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Efirst%20paper%3C%2Fa%3E%20highlights%20how%20researchers%20completely%20sequenced%20an%20individual's%20Y%20chromosome%20for%20the%20first%20time%2C%20adding%20over%20half%20the%20genetic%20information%20that%20was%20previously%20missing.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EChromosomes%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fmy.clevelandclinic.org%2Fhealth%2Fbody%2F23064-dna-genes--chromosomes%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ecarry%20DNA%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%20the%20nucleus%20of%20every%20cell%20in%20the%20human%20body.%20The%20rungs%20of%20DNA's%20ladder%20consist%20of%20base%20pairs%20(adenine%2C%20cytosine%2C%20thymine%2C%20and%20guanine)%20of%20which%20there%20are%20about%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.genome.gov%2Fgenetics-glossary%2FBase-Pair%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E3%20billion%3C%2Fa%3E%20in%20the%20complete%20human%20genome.%20Over%2062%20million%20of%20them%20belong%20to%20the%20Y%20chromosome.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%3Cstrong%3E%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cstrong%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%222000%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22A%20labeled%20diagram%20of%20a%20chromosome%2C%20DNA%2C%20and%20the%20base%20pairs%20adenine%2C%20cytosine%2C%20guanine%2C%20and%20thymine%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F64e69246912f290019aa2752%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221500%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EChromosomes%20carry%20DNA%20in%20the%20cell%20nucleus%20and%20encode%20genetic%20information.%3Cp%3EVectorMine%2FiStock%2FGetty%20Images%20Plus%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20new%20sequencing%20added%20over%2030%20million%20base%20pairs%20to%20fill%20in%20significant%20gaps%20in%20the%20human%20genome%20reference.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAnother%20group%20of%20scientists%20sequenced%20an%20additional%2043%20Y%20chromosomes%20from%20people%20all%20over%20the%20world%20for%20the%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdoi.org%2F10.1038%2Fs41586-023-06425-6%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Esecond%20paper%3C%2Fa%3E%20to%20get%20a%20more%20complete%20picture%20of%20variations%20across%20individuals%20and%20populations.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BIt%20really%20took%20a%20star-studded%20cast%20of%20people%20to%20make%20sure%20that%20this%20was%20an%20accurate%20reference%20because%20we%20understand%20how%20important%20it%20is%2C%20every%20single%20base%20on%20that%20reference%2C%26quot%3B%20said%20Karen%20Miga%2C%20one%20of%20the%20authors%20of%20the%20first%20study%20and%20co-founder%20of%20the%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fsites.google.com%2Fucsc.edu%2Ft2tworkinggroup%2Fin-the-news%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3ETelomere-to-Telomere%3C%2Fa%3E%20Consortium.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3EWhat's%20so%20tricky%20about%20the%20Y%20chromosome%3F%C2%A0%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EMost%20people%20have%2022%20pairs%20of%20chromosomes%20and%20two%20sex%20chromosomes%2C%20usually%20either%20XX%20or%20XY.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20other%20sex%20chromosome%2C%20the%20X%20chromosome%2C%20has%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fmedlineplus.gov%2Fgenetics%2Fchromosome%2Fx%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Emore%20than%20double%3C%2Fa%3E%20the%20base%20pairs%20of%20the%20Y%2C%20but%20it%20was%20far%20easier%20to%20sequence.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThat's%20because%20the%20Y%20chromosome%20is%20%26quot%3Bthe%20most%20complex%2C%20most%20repetitive%20chromosome%2C%26quot%3B%20said%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcampusdirectory.ucsc.edu%2Fcd_detail%3Fuid%3Dmcechova%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EMonika%20Cechova%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20a%20postdoctoral%20researcher%20at%20the%20University%20of%20California%2C%20Santa%20Cruz.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cfigure%3E%3Cimg%20width%3D%5C%221365%5C%22%20alt%3D%5C%22Geneticist%20Karen%20Miga%20sequences%20the%20human%20Y%20chromosome%20in%20the%20University%20of%20California%2C%20Santa%20Cruz%20lab%5C%22%20charset%3D%5C%22%5C%22%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F64e62c914c17ff0019bb1a1e%3Fformat%3Djpeg%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%221026%5C%22%3E%3Cfigcaption%3EKaren%20Miga%20was%20one%20of%20the%20researchers%20involved%20in%20fully%20sequencing%20the%20human%20Y%20chromosome.%3Cp%3ECarolyn%20Lagattuta%2FUC%20Santa%20Cruz%3C%2Fp%3E%3C%2Ffigcaption%3E%3C%2Ffigure%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThe%20human%20Y%20chromosome%20is%20like%20a%20hall%20of%20mirrors%2C%26quot%3B%20said%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fcarta.anthropogeny.org%2Fusers%2Fpascal-gagneux%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EPascal%20Gagneux%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20professor%20of%20pathology%20and%20anthropology%20at%20UC%20San%20Diego%2C%20who%20wasn't%20involved%20in%20either%20paper.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThere%20are%20tons%20of%20repeating%20sequences%20that%20are%20palindromes%2C%20reading%20the%20same%20forward%20as%20backward%2C%20like%20the%20words%20mom%2C%20peep%2C%20and%20kayak.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BYou're%20just%20surrounded%20by%20lots%20of%20similar%20sequences%2C%20and%20you%20don't%20know%20in%20which%20direction%20they%20go%2C%26quot%3B%20said%20Gagneaux%2C%20who%20is%20associated%20with%20one%20of%20the%20researchers%2C%20Evan%20Eichler%2C%20through%20the%20Center%20for%20Academic%20Research%20and%20Training%20in%20Anthropogeny%3Cem%3E.%3C%2Fem%3E%3Cstrong%3E%3Cbr%3E%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHowever%2C%20understanding%20these%20palindromic%20regions%20is%20important%20because%20they%20code%20for%20processes%20like%20sperm%20production.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThese%20repeating%20sequences%20also%20result%20in%20gene%20pairs%20that%20may%20serve%20as%20backups%20in%20case%20of%20mutation%2C%20helping%20genes%20continue%20to%20function%2C%20Cechova%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EUsing%20an%20algorithm%20to%20read%20the%20sequence%20helped%20the%20researchers%20keep%20track%20of%20the%20gene%20copies%20and%20where%20they%20belonged.%C2%A0%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E%3Cstrong%3E%3Cstrong%3EThe%20repetitious%20Y%20chromosome%3C%2Fstrong%3E%20%3Cbr%3E%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EFurther%20complicating%20the%20sequencing%20were%20the%20two%20satellite%20DNA%20regions%20that%20researchers%20didn't%20know%20much%20about.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BHere%20you%20had%20tens%20of%20millions%20of%20bases%20that%20were%20just%20seemingly%20repeating%20the%20same%20paragraph%20over%20and%20over%2C%26quot%3B%20Miga%20said.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20function%20of%20the%20long%2C%20repetitive%20sequences%20on%20one%20of%20the%20arms%20of%20the%20chromosome%20is%20still%20a%20mystery%2C%20but%20there's%20a%20better%20way%20to%20map%20them%20than%20there%20was%2020%20years%20ago.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EA%20newer%20sequencing%20technique%20read%20longer%20chunks%20of%20DNA%20that%20were%20easier%20to%20piece%20back%20together%20than%20the%20smaller%20fragments%20geneticists%20used%20for%20earlier%20genome%20references.%3Cstrong%3E%3Cbr%3E%3C%2Fstrong%3E%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EResearchers%20from%20the%20NHGRI%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.genome.gov%2Fnews%2Fnews-release%2Fresearchers-assemble-the-first-complete-sequence-of-a-human-y-chromosome%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ecompared%3C%2Fa%3E%20sequencing%20the%20Y%20chromosome%20to%20trying%20to%20assemble%20a%20book%20that%20had%20been%20cut%20into%20strips%2C%20where%20half%20the%20sentences%20were%20all%20exactly%20the%20same.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EYou%20don't%20want%20the%20same%20words%20from%20page%2045%20to%20end%20up%20on%20page%20108.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BIt%20was%20always%20irritating%20knowing%20we%20were%20missing%20half%20the%20Y%20whenever%20we%20tried%20to%20do%20any%20reference-based%20analysis%2C%26quot%3B%20Arang%20Rhie%2C%20a%20staff%20scientist%20at%20the%20National%20Human%20Genome%20Research%20Institute%20and%20the%20lead%20author%20on%20the%20single-sequence%20paper%2C%20said%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.eurekalert.org%2Fnews-releases%2F999037%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Ein%20a%20statement%3C%2Fa%3E.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3EThe%20worldwide%20Y%20chromosome%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3EFor%20the%20single-sequence%20paper%2C%20researchers%20sequenced%20the%20Y%20chromosome%20of%20a%20single%20individual%20of%20European%20descent%2C%20known%20as%20the%20HG002%20genome.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAll%20human%20genomes%20share%2099.9%25%20of%20the%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.genome.gov%2Fdna-day%2F15-ways%2Fhuman-genomic-variation%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Esame%20base%20pairs%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20but%20that%200.1%25%20difference%20can%20have%20an%20impact%20on%20health.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhile%20the%20HG002%20Y%20chromosome%20sequence%20provides%20an%20important%20baseline%20for%20genetic%20comparison%2C%20the%20second%20paper%20from%20the%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.jax.org%2Fpersonalized-medicine%2Fthe-jackson-laboratory-for-genomic-medicine%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EJackson%20Laboratory%20for%20Genomic%20Medicine%3C%2Fa%3E%20shows%20just%20how%20many%20variations%20there%20are%20between%20individuals.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ESelected%20from%20the%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.internationalgenome.org%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3E1000%20Genomes%20Project%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20about%20half%20the%2043%20individuals%20have%20African%20ancestry%2C%20which%20is%20important%20for%20representing%20genetic%20diversity%2C%20Gagneux%20said.%C2%A0%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAmong%20the%20several%20dozen%20Y%20chromosomes%20the%20researchers%20looked%20at%2C%20they%20saw%20marked%20differences%20in%20size%20and%20structure.%20For%20example%2C%20they%20found%20a%20range%20in%20the%20number%20of%20base%20pairs%2C%20from%2045.2%20million%20to%2084.9%20million.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EBecause%20of%20all%20the%20gaps%20in%20the%20Y%20chromosome%20genome%20reference%2C%20researchers%20haven't%20fully%20understood%20how%20the%20chromosome%20contributes%20to%20overall%20health.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20hope%20is%20that%20the%20new%20research%20will%20give%20scientists%20more%20knowledge%20about%20how%20genetic%20differences%20affect%20infertility%2C%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Faffiliate.insider.com%3Fh%3D6dd39c37f6e495618065211adc7a3361c653d